&gt; &gt;  &gt; Here, the abstract keyword does nothing useful. It&#39;s 
&gt; likely that when
&gt; &gt;  &gt; Kent and/or Erich created this class, Eclipse added the 
&gt; &quot;abstract&quot;
&gt; &gt;  &gt; keyword for them and they never bothered to remove it.
&gt; &gt;  &gt;
&gt; &gt;  &gt; For that matter, the methods don&#39;t need to be marked 
&gt; &quot;public&quot; either.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; There is one use to leaving the superfluous &quot;public 
&gt; abstract&quot; modifiers:
&gt; &gt; if you decide to change an interface into an abstract class, or vice
&gt; &gt; versa, it&#39;s one less textual step you need to perform.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Doesn&#39;t JUnit predate Eclipse?
&gt; 
&gt; A fine point. It might therefore have been Visual Age for 
&gt; Java throwing 
&gt; that stuff in. I seem to recall that it did that. :)
